<p>I’ve noticed that on many teams I’ve been a part of, not just at Mozilla, people tend to think that I am “lashing out”, or argumentative, and this, they assume, is not productive. I disagree entirely.</p>
<p><a href=\"https://wikipedia.org/wiki/Peltzman_effect\">The Peltzman Effect</a> shows us that when people perceive a low level of risk (ie when they feel protected) they act less cautiously, and when they perceive a high level of risk they act more cautiously. It is my hypothesis that the same rule can be applied to intelligence. That is to say that when people feel more protected they will think less, and when they feel they have less protection they think more.</p>
<p>So how can this hypothesis be applied to team work?</p>
<p>Well before we dive in to the counterintuitive, let’s evaluate the concept of the yes-man, otherwise known as a sycophanct. The sycophanct does not use his/her own intelligence, ever, they always say “Yes” to their leader(s), and it should be obvious to all why a team of sycophancts would produce bad products. But why does the sycophanct behave this way? the answer is simple, they do it because it is low risk. If the idea is a good one, they agreed with a good idea, if the idea is a bad one then they cannot be blammed for it, because it was the leader who decided it was good, not the sycophanct.</p>
<p>So since we all know intuitively that a team of yes-men is obviously bad, why is it that some people think a team of people that are willing to say “No” is not good? The answer I suspect is pride.</p>
<p>In a team of people that are willing to say “No” pride is at risk, and in a team where people are concerned more about their pride than the productivity of the team someone that is willing to say “No” stands out, and risks being called a bad team-mate.</p>
<p>In my opionin personal attacks are unproductive, but attacking ideas should be completely necessary in producing an effective team, which would be most capable of producing the highest quality products.</p>
<p><a href=\"https://wikipedia.org/wiki/Peltzman_effect\">The Peltzman Effect</a> shows us this.</p>
<p>If a member of a team feels no risk in submitting bad ideas to their team, then they will do so, because good ideas take more time to think through. However if a member of a team feels higher risk associated to submitting bad ideas, like having the idea publicly denounced, then they will think about it more, and produce a higher quality idea. Furthermore, if after thinking about their idea long and hard, they submit something that has flaws, then in a team of yes-men the poor idea will not be challenged, whereas in a team of no-men the idea will be challenged until the highest quality idea that the whole team is capable of is produced. This doesn’t mean that everyone will agree on the final decision of course, ultimately when there is disagreement and no way to bridge the gap, someone will have to make the final decision, and this person should be a cool headed mediator in my opinion, someone that is capable of collecting all of the facts, and calibrating their own opinions and emotions.</p>
<h3>Conclusion for Mozilla</h3>
<h4>Secret Meetings Are Bad</h4>
<p>In Vidyo/Skype meetings, who said what is lost, and therefore it is a safe place for people for submit bad ideas. Instead all discussion of any important should be written down and made public. If someone is worried about their pride call them out on it, they should expect that their ideas will be attacked, and they should be able to tell the difference between that and a personal attack. The former should be expected, and the latter should not be tolerated.</p>
<h4>Mediators Not Leaders</h4>
<p>We should not have leaders, but instead we should have mediators. If the people that are most passoniate about their own ideas are promoted then we will have teams of yes-men producing crap, if we instead promote the mediators, then we will have effective teams producing awesomeness.</p>
<h4>Drop The Torpedoes!</h4>
<p>If you are on a team, and you don’t agree with some idea, then be publically vocal about why you think it is bad, remember it is important to attack ideas and not the people behind them, this doesn’t mean you can’t use their name, but it does mean you should try to refrain from doing so. If you lean towards agreeing with the idea, then play devil’s advocate. The important part here is to be public, because that increases the risk for your team mates in having bad ideas, because they will be associated with the bad idea, and that should make them think harder next time.</p>
<h4>Rhino Skin</h4>
<p>“If you’re gonna be dumb, you gotta be tough” – Roger Alan Wade</p>
<h4>We All Make Mistakes</h4>
<p>Nobody is perfect, try to remember that. Those that smirk at you when you fall down, make a mistake, or have a bad idea are forgetting that they too are fallible, and if you remember this, then you will be not only wiser than they, but also a more beautiful human being.</p>
<p>We are all human. Be forgiving.</p>" nil nil "759c268cd3419f34fd02f91d78a41e4b") (526 (21000 35646 147656) "http://mike.kaply.com/2013/08/11/keyword-search-updated/" "Michael Kaply: Keyword Search Updated" "Mike Kaply" "Mon, 12 Aug 2013 01:54:29 +0000" "<p>
