<br />  <a href=\"http://feeds.wordpress.com/1.0/gocomments/mzeier.wordpress.com/1259/\" rel=\"nofollow\"><img alt=\"\" border=\"0\" src=\"http://feeds.wordpress.com/1.0/comments/mzeier.wordpress.com/1259/\" /></a> <img alt=\"\" border=\"0\" height=\"1\" src=\"http://stats.wordpress.com/b.gif?host=mrz.velvet.org&blog=52485401&post=1259&subd=mzeier&ref=&feed=1\" width=\"1\" />" nil nil "77d85d77ccad309d29a4d14c13e48382") (519 (20996 43043 433900) "http://seanmonstar.com/post/57737181854" "Sean McArthur: Gmail Bridge for Persona" nil "Thu, 08 Aug 2013 22:22:44 +0000" "<p>Since <a href=\"http://seanmonstar.com/post/27636319508/moved-to-identity\">shifting to the Identity team</a> last year, I’ve been working hard on making Persona a true solution to the login problem of the web. As I said then:</p>
<blockquote>
<p>If we do our job right, eventually when my friends ask me what I do, I can say: I helped make it so you no longer need to use passwords everywhere. I helped make your online identity more secure. I helped make signing into the Internet awesomer.</p>
</blockquote>
<p>We’re getting closer.</p>
<h3>What is the Gmail Bridge?</h3>
<p>Today, we’re announcing to the world that our <a href=\"http://identity.mozilla.com/post/57712756801/persona-makes-signing-in-easy-for-gmail-users\">Gmail Identity Bridge is online</a>. Excuse me. What? No, I’m fine. It’s alright, it’s actually quite simple.</p>
<p>The way <a href=\"http://lloyd.io/how-browserid-works\">Persona normally works</a>, after checking to see if your email provider natively supports the protocol, is that Persona will fallback to what we call a secondary provider. This is the point where most users end up creating a password for Persona, and then going to their email to verify to us that they really own their email address. If the email provider <em>did</em> support the protocol, they would get sent over to them to authenticate, and we’d step out of the way.</p>
<p>So, we made an <a href=\"http://identity.mozilla.com/post/56526022621/what-is-an-identity-bridge\">Identity Bridge</a> that we host, and uses Google’s OpenID endpoint to verify the user. The experience is pretty much exactly what it should feel like if there was native support from Google.</p>
<h3>Why this matters</h3>
<p>With both Gmail and Yahoo bridges online, <em>over half of all users</em> are just a couple clicks away from logging in with Persona.</p>
<p>So how does this affect you? If you have a website that has user accounts, you can switch to using <a href=\"http://davidwalsh.name/introduction-persona\">Persona as your authentication system</a>. In most cases, it should be a <strong>better</strong> experience for your users, and easier for you.</p>
<p>If you don’t have a website, you can still help. Find a website you log in to frequently, and ask them to implement Persona. Tell them about this new bridging. Push for the change.</p>
<p>Soon, everyone will notice: <strong>we made signing into the Internet awesomer.</strong></p>" nil nil "bcce5e7dcad6a7ff8b14c8692a15917f") (518 (20996 43043 433042) "http://work.erikvold.com/ux/2013/08/08/mo-usage-mo-problems.html" "Erik Vold: Mo Usage Mo Problems" "Erik Vold" "Thu, 08 Aug 2013 07:00:00 +0000" "<h3>The Facade</h3>
<p>How can a serious UX designer think that designing for the majority is all that is necessary? a good design is not merely useful to the users that hardly use a product, or are new to a product. A truely good design is instead good for those that use the product infrequently and those that use it frequently.</p>
<p>A good song is not a good song if you initially hate it, nor is it a good song if you liked it at first and then hated it after a few listens. If you like the song after a few years it is highly unlikely that you will hate it in a decade, thus it is a good song. If you dislike the song at any period in that interval then it was not well designed.</p>
<p>Furthermore the more you listen to a song, the more you should enjoy it, because you take more from it.</p>
<p>This is why Beethoven was a master composer.</p>
<h3><a href=\"https://wikipedia.org/wiki/Boiling_frog\">Boiling A Frog</a></h3>
<p>It’s said that if a frog is placed in boiling water, then it will quickly jump out, but if it is placed in cold water that is slowly heated, it will be cooked to death.</p>
<p>This is not a good analogy to use for UX design. A good UX designer should not be focused on cooking their frogs, they should be focused on providing awesome ponds with lots of flies for their frogs.</p>
<h3>Conclusion</h3>
<p>People should not be punished the more they use a product, instead they should always be rewarded.</p>" nil nil "2ca7ed60f77bf957aba540edcac9688a") (517 (20996 43043 432554) "http://work.erikvold.com/mozilla/2013/08/08/mozilla-is-open-global-and-async.html" "Erik Vold: Mozilla Is An Open Global Asynchronous Community" "Erik Vold" "Thu, 08 Aug 2013 07:00:00 +0000" "<p>I love Mozilla, it is an exemplar of openness. For example there are no secret meetings at Mozilla like there are at Microsoft, Apple, Google, or the NSA. All discussions are in the open, and anyone around the globe can participate, asynchronously.</p>
<p>In order to facilitate Mozilla’s openness and globalness the community is also completely asynchronous. This means that timezones are not an issue at all, nor is language, because everyone has the opportunity to read the openness, do their translations if necessary, and respond when their thoughts have been developed in the timezone in which they operate, and employees always respond.</p>
<p>I am in no way being facetious.</p>" nil nil "4eb926e3aaf9fffb4be345dc87d13422") (516 (20995 27816 393822) "http://feedproxy.google.com/~r/SoftwareIsHardPlanetMozilla/~3/28PYcKGEpdc/" "Jan Odvarko: Firebug Extension: FirePicker =?utf-8?Q?=E2=80=93?= Pick your color" "Honza" "Thu, 08 Aug 2013 09:20:59 +0000" "<p>I couldn't miss this nifty extension in my series of posts about Firebug extensions. It's a small plugin focused on one thing and working great!</p>
