t need to request or create a talos.zip since we use the talos repo directly</li></ul></ul><li><b>It makes easier developing and testing new talos changes.</b></li><ul><li>We can make configuration changes in an easier manner and it is locked to a given changest rather than affecting a whole branch</li><ul><li>It can ride the trains</li><li>It only requires changes to talos.json</li><li>This makes testing new configuration changes on try easier</li></ul><li>Mozharness also gives us a lot of flexibility</li></ul><ul><ul><li>Including a finer control on the usage of Python packages</li></ul></ul><li><b>We even have mach support!</b></li><ul><li>This makes it trivial for developers to run talos in their beloved objdirs (<a href=\"http://technotroph.wordpress.com/2013/07/29/talos-mozharness-is-now-integrated-with-mach/\">blog post</a>)</li></ul></ul><br /><br /><div><b>Cons:</b></div><ul><li>We have to take a <a href=\"https://bugzilla.mozilla.org/show_bug.cgi?id=713055#c60\">perf hit on ts tests</a></li></ul><br /><br /><br /><hr /><a href=\"http://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-sa/3.0/\" rel=\"license\"><img alt=\"Creative Commons License\" src=\"http://i.creativecommons.org/l/by-nc-sa/3.0/88x31.png\" style=\"border-width: 0;\" /></a><br />This work by <a href=\"http://armenzg.blogspot.com/\" rel=\"cc:attributionurl\">Zambrano Gasparnian, Armen</a> is licensed under a <a href=\"http://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-sa/3.0/\" rel=\"license\">Creative Commons Attribution-Noncommercial-Share Alike 3.0 Unported License</a>." nil nil "1f87b25af3e086a959a236c9e2867439") (444 (20984 50462 37634) "http://feedproxy.google.com/~r/BenjaminKerensaDotComMozilla/~3/KlexXj0JQ-M/oscon-mozilla-awesome" "Benjamin Kerensa: OSCON + Mozilla = Awesome" "Benjamin Kerensa" "Tue, 30 Jul 2013 12:00:18 +0000" "<div class=\"wp-caption aligncenter\" id=\"attachment_1995\" style=\"width: 310px;\"><a class=\"thickbox no_icon\" href=\"http://cdn.benjaminkerensa.com/wp-content/uploads/2013/07/DSC_1287.jpg\" title=\"DSC 1287 300x199 OSCON + Mozilla = Awesome\"><img alt=\"DSC 1287 300x199 OSCON + Mozilla = Awesome\" class=\"size-medium wp-image-1995\" height=\"199\" src=\"http://cdn.benjaminkerensa.com/wp-content/uploads/2013/07/DSC_1287-300x199.jpg\" title=\"OSCON + Mozilla = Awesome\" width=\"300\" /></a><p class=\"wp-caption-text\">Me and Tim O’Reilly</p></div>
<p>Last week I was at O’Reilly Open Source Convention representing the Mozilla Community and meeting with folks to talk about some of the cool things going on in the Mozilla Community.</p>
<p>This year was especially exciting because Mozilla sponsored Community Leadership Summit the weekend before which had an amazing turnout and had several Mozillians in attendance. Even better, OSCON itself had a great line up of Mozillians speaking about technology and topics they are passionate about.</p>
<p>Towards the end of the week several of us gathered and I hosted a Mozilla Birds of Feather session which saw a small but good turnout of developers and even students from Oregon State University Open Source Labs. It was interesting because even the non-Mozillians had strong ties to the Mozilla community in one manner or another.</p>
<p>I think OSCON was a great opportunity for Mozillians this year to engage the greater open source community and do some networking but I think next year we can have a even larger role and perhaps a booth where we can do some Firefox OS evangelism.</p>
<img height=\"1\" src=\"http://feeds.feedburner.com/~r/BenjaminKerensaDotComMozilla/~4/KlexXj0JQ-M\" width=\"1\" />" nil nil "7228e39465174dc79f53ebaaaf2d3056") (443 (20984 50462 37221) "http://work.erikvold.com/ux/2013/07/30/do-not-track-dark-pattern.html" "Erik Vold: Do Not Track - Dark Pattern" "Erik Vold" "Tue, 30 Jul 2013 07:00:00 +0000" "<p>There is design concept called <a href=\"http://darkpatterns.org/what_is_a_dark_pattern/\">dark patterns</a>, they are not mistakes, they are carefully crafted with a solid understanding of human psychology, and they do not have the user’s interests in mind.</p>
<h3>Dark Pattern: False Features</h3>
<h4>Definition</h4>
<p>Providing and touting a feature that does absolutely nothing, something completely different, or worse the opposite of what it claims to do.</p>
<h4>Example: Do Not Track</h4>
<p><a href=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Do_Not_Track_Policy\">Do Not Track</a> is not what its’ title says, it is a completey anti-intuitive feature whose title and function are completely different. The title is meant to stir up emotion (after all who wants to be tracked?) and the meaning has nothing to do with tracking, it has to do with advertisting. Furthermore the “feature” does absolutely nothing, it is completely ignorable (meaning websites can choose to ignore it), and so it is typically ignored.</p>
<p>I first discovered this dark pattern when filing <a href=\"https://bugzilla.mozilla.org/show_bug.cgi?id=858839\">Bug 858839</a>.</p>
<p>I remember when Mozilla first implemented the “feature”, there was a lot of self boasting (which still continues) about being the first browser to implement this do nothing feature, and ofcourse every other browser quickly supported it because it is in fact a do nothing feature which produced a ton of hype. The fact is that even Mozilla web developers ignore the DNT header (see <a href=\"https://bugzilla.mozilla.org/show_bug.cgi?id=858839\">Bug 858839</a>), and use obfuscated explanations that “tracking” really means “advertising” in order to divert attention from the dark pattern.</p>
<p>For more information see <a href=\"http://alistapart.com/article/dark-patterns-deception-vs.-honesty-in-ui-design\">this article</a>.</p>
<p>For more dark patterns see <a href=\"http://darkpatterns.org/\">darkpatterns.org</a>.</p>" nil nil "608b35607726ac4f12e06522a4cfbe7e") (442 (20984 50462 36739) "http://work.erikvold.com/jetpack/2013/07/30/good-first-jetpack-bugs.html" "Erik Vold: Good First Jetpack Bugs" "Erik Vold" "Tue, 30 Jul 2013 07:00:00 +0000" "<p>I’ve taken the time to tag a bunch of Add-on SDK (aka Jetpack) bugs which I thought were good first bugs, <a href=\"https://bugzilla.mozilla.org/buglist.cgi?list_id=7345714&columnlist=bug_severity%2Cpriority%2Cassigned_to%2Cbug_status%2Ctarget_milestone%2Cresolution%2Cshort_desc%2Cchangeddate&query_based_on=jetpack-good-1st-bugs&status_whiteboard_type=allwordssubstr&query_format=advanced&status_whiteboard=%5Bgood%20first%20bug%5D&bug_status=UNCONFIRMED&bug_status=NEW&bug_status=ASSIGNED&bug_status=REOPENED&bug_status=VERIFIED&product=Add-on%20SDK&known_name=jetpack-good-1st-bugs\">which can be found here</a>. The team will be adding bugs to this list when we find more good first bugs, so check it out if you ever feel like you have the time and desire to make a contribution.</p>
<p>For more information of how to make a contribution <a href=\"https://github.com/mozilla/addon-sdk/wiki/contribute\">see this wiki page</a>. There are many reviewers now, and we can provide you with a lot of help, so feel free to ask!</p>" nil nil "7058f33e5a4372abf5b56864f77c36b5") (441 (20984 50462 36395) "http://work.erikvold.com/firefox/2013/07/30/how-to-spot-a-white-elephant-design.html" "Erik Vold: How To Spot A White Elephant Design" "Erik Vold" "Tue, 30 Jul 2013 07:00:00 +0000" "<p>In the time that I have spent as a Mozillian, first as a contributor starting in 2010, then as an employee just over a year ago, I have seen quite a funny array of <a href=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/White_elephant\">white elephants</a> and I think the company really needs to do something about this awful trend. After all reacting late is almost as bad as not reacting at all.</p>
<p>So here are some of my tips on how to spot a white elephant design:</p>
<h3>1. Give It Resources!</h3>
<p>Will the design require a ton of development before any prototyping can be done?</p>
<h3>2. Straight To Product!</h3>
<p>Is the designer claiming that the idea should just land in Firefox immediately when it could obviously be an extension first?</p>
<h3>3. Add It To That New Thing!</h3>
<p>Is the designer claiming that adding the design to some new product (which is already in development) would be a good test bed for the design?</p>
<h3>4. It’s Going To Need Marketing!</h3>
<p>Is the designer claiming that the design will require marketing?</p>
<h3>5. It’s Totally Better I Swear!</h3>
<p>If the designer drops dead tomorrow, is there no one else that can pick up the design and speak for it?</p>
<h3>Conclusion</h3>
<p>If you can say yes to any of the above, then beware, because you might be looking at a white elephant design.</p>" nil nil "ca6be5d2d9d9e663cf999225182c44c9") (440 (20984 50462 35925) "http://dbaron.org/log/20130729-debug-builds" "L. David Baron: Why debug builds (and assertions) are important" "David Baron" "Tue, 30 Jul 2013 00:35:00 +0000" "<div>
