<div class=\"zemanta-pixie\"><a class=\"zemanta-pixie-a\" href=\"http://www.zemanta.com/?px\" title=\"Enhanced by Zemanta\"><img alt=\"Enhanced by Zemanta\" class=\"zemanta-pixie-img\" src=\"http://img.zemanta.com/zemified_e.png?x-id=4d63f09f-1f86-4767-91f3-069345b3a450\" /></a></div>" nil nil "92ef67271d7041f1e475b63e0cc09701") (427 (20984 50462 22204) "http://blog.bitops.com/blog/2013/07/26/mobile-graphics-pushing-forward/" "Vladimir =?utf-8?B?VnVracSHZXZpxIc6?= Mobile Graphics Pushing Forward" nil "Fri, 26 Jul 2013 14:06:00 +0000" "<p>SIGGRAPH was this week, and while I didn’t attend, I had a few thoughts about some of the announcements that were made.  Mozilla is pretty serious about wanting to increase the level of graphics capability accessible to the web on both the desktop and mobile.  As some sharp observers may have noticed, we (and by we, I mean largely Guillaume Abadie) at Mozilla <a href=\"https://wiki.mozilla.org/Platform/GFX/WebGL2\">have been working quietly</a> on implementing the bulk of OpenGL ES 3.0 capabilities as extensions to WebGL 1 (all disabled by pref by default, for now!).  “WebGL 2”, when it’s specified, will likely just be the union of all of these extensions, but all on by default.  A WebGL 2 tied to OpenGL ES 3.0 is a big step towards exposing more modern graphics capabilities, but it’s still behind what’s current on the desktop.  What we need is a unified API on both desktop and mobile that can allow access to the maximum capabilities of each.</p>
<p>NVIDIA’s <a href=\"http://blogs.nvidia.com/blog/2013/07/24/kepler-to-mobile/\">announcement of Project Logan</a>, their next-generation mobile processor, is pretty exciting.  By bringing desktop-class GL 4.4 in addition to ES 2 and ES 3 to mobile, I’m hoping that it will spur the mobile industry to push the mobile graphics envelope forward, instead of stagnating for years as it did with ES2.  Having the <a href=\"http://android-developers.blogspot.ca/2013/07/android-43-and-updated-developer-tools.html\">latest version of Android support ES 3</a> is a good start, but it’s still behind what’s available on the desktop.  While having OpenGL 4.4 isn’t immediately going to help WebGL – we still need to deliver a consistent API for the web – the presence of the “desktop” API on a mobile platform blurs the line between the two.  The difference between what can be done on a traditional desktop or laptop PC vs a tablet or a smartphone is shrinking rapidly.  The difference in graphics capabilities should shrink as well.</p>
<p>Under the hood, Firefox can take advantage of the additional capabilities even if they aren’t exposed to content through WebGL.  We currently have many paths to access the various hardware acceleration APIs on different platforms.  Being able to access desktop-class GL on a mobile device will enable us to bring some acceleration paths to mobile that should make Firefox really shine on Logan-class mobile hardware.  I’m looking forward to getting my hands on a Logan-powered device and running some content through Firefox for Android!</p>" nil nil "0e24bcc6cbcd0fa2cdafb0909f813ead") (426 (20984 50462 21710) "http://work.erikvold.com/pathfinder/2013/07/26/pathfinder-storage.html" "Erik Vold: Pathfinder Storage" "Erik Vold" "Fri, 26 Jul 2013 07:00:00 +0000" "<p><a href=\"http://work.erikvold.com/jetpack/2013/07/15/do-not-use-simple-storage.html\">It is my opinion that simple-storage should not be used</a>. It is true that it is simple to use, and if you need to prototype something quickly then I would suggest using simple-storage, but if you need something professional then I would stick to my original opinion and suggest against it. When I stated this opinion I said it was because it was writing to disk every 5 minutes, and at the time I knew we could optimize that a bit which the jetpack team is working on in <a href=\"https://bugzilla.mozilla.org/show_bug.cgi?id=893276\">bug 893276</a>, but there are actually deeper issues with the module, that was just the most ridiculous one.</p>
<p>The module was designed to mimic localStorage, which has a synchronous API, which is always a bad sign. This means that when you first access the storage the whole file (which by design could be as much as 5MB with default settings) is read from disk, meanwhile blocking the main thread until this reading is complete. This is not fixable and will not change due to the synchronous API design. The second issue is the default limit of 5MB, <a href=\"http://dev.w3.org/html5/webstorage/#disk-space\">it’s a completely arbitrary decision</a> made by Ian Hickson from Google which we merely followed.</p>
<p>So I promised I would make a sane alternative in the <a href=\"https://github.com/erikvold/addon-pathfinder\">Add-on Pathfinder</a>, and I’m ready to present that to you now. I’ve simply called the module <code>storage</code> and it is completely async, it has no size limit, and it will simply save a string blob.</p>
<p>Here is an example:</p>
<pre><code>let storage = require('pathfinder/storage');
let originalData = JSON.stringify(myData);
let savePromise = storage.set({ data: originalData, charset: 'UTF-8' });
savePromise.then(function({ data: dataSaved }) {
let fetchPromise = storage.get({ charset: 'UTF-8' });
fetchPromise.then(function({ data: dataFetched }) {
console.log(dataSaved == dataFetched); // true
console.log(dataFetched == originalData); // true
});
});</code></pre>
<p>Clearly it’s not as simple to use as simple-storage, but it is easy, and it is async so it will not block the main thread no matter how much data you choose to use, and therefore the UX will be far better.</p>" nil nil "656522903322e12cfb9d09935cdfa30b") (425 (20984 50462 21172) "http://work.erikvold.com/2013/07/26/on-the-fallacy-of-design.html" "Erik Vold: On The Fallacy Of Design" "Erik Vold" "Fri, 26 Jul 2013 07:00:00 +0000" "<p>Good design is not made, it is enabled. In other words design is not constructed from the top down, but instead it is made possible from the ground up.</p>
<p>The watch is not constructed by the watchmaker in a vacuum, the watchmaker does not invent the atoms with which the watch is made, nor does he invent the combination of atoms in to molecules, nor molecules in to compounds, and so on. The watchmaker merely picks from the materials available to him, which make the watch possible, and develops the watch from those pieces. He is merely picking a wise combination choice from the entropy that was made available.</p>
<p>It is easy to see that the greatest designs were not constructed, but enabled. It is equally easy to see that some of the poorest designs were constructed and not enabled. Let’s look at economics, since I am interested in the subject at the moment.</p>
<p>Every learned person knows that Capitalism was not designed by anyone, it developed from the ground up, out of the development of tools came the concept of possesions, out of possessions came the concept of trade, and out of trade came Capitalism. Communism on the other hand was constructed out of a concept called morals which is an equally if not worse designed concept, which was developed out of emotions, which our brains have developed haphazardly in the vacuum that is in our skulls.</p>
<p>Note carefully that I have not said that all ground up designs are good ones, that is certainly not the case, in fact the majority of bad designs are ground up, merely because of the nature of entropy. I said that good designs are wisely selected from the ground up, and those designs made in a vacuum are always, or nearly always failures.</p>
<p>Let’s look at some of Mozilla’s products from the past (this is a blog called Voldzilla after all), and see if we can’t use this way of thinking to explain why the bad designs were bad, and why the good designs were good.</p>
<p>I don’t want to hurt anyone’s feelings, but that is probably unavoidable if we allow our emotions to rule us, something I am no less guilty of than anyone else. I am not trying to pick on individuals here, I admire everyone that I work with, my goal is merely to point out the fallacy of design, so that we made avoid it and create better products and be more productive.</p>
<p>Ubiquity started out as a product that was enabled by great designs that existed before it, it took the concept of command line tools, the internet, web service apis, web technologies like HTML + CSS and JavaScript, and Firefox add-ons to make a product that blew my mind and many others, it was an example of fantastic design. Then the concept of Natural Language Processing was slapped on and the product fell apart, perhaps more quickly than it materialized.</p>
<p>Languages were made from the ground up, trying to pretend that we can write a program with a top down approach to combine all of these languages was an idea made in a vacuum.</p>
<p>Jetpack took successful concepts from UserScripts, Add-ons, CommonJS, and Ubiquity to make a product that is extremely well designed, but the product has stagnated due to the desire to shove ever more concepts in to the products.</p>
<p>Designing Jetpack to be the end all replacement for old school add-ons which solves all of our issues with current add-ons is an idea made in a vacuum which could kill the project. One day it may be the stepping stone we need to make such a product, but that golden product cannot be designed in a vacuum, we have to build the pieces that enable us to get there first.</p>
<p>UserScripts have been a major success, almost all major browsers have adopted them, not daring to leave all of the glory to Firefox. They are a great example of ground up design. No one designed them in a vacuum, the pieces that were needed were put in to place long before the idea was hatched. Pieces like the internat, browsers, web sites, JavaScript, then volla, UserScripts! The design was enabled long before it was wisely selected.</p>
<p>UserStyles have largely the same story as UserScripts, the former having been developed after the latter.</p>
<p>FirefoxOS has uses ideas from existing smart phones, old flip phones, Linux, Firefox, and various Web technologies to produce a product from the ground up. There are many problems for which we do not have answers, which is a good sign that the product was not been designed from the top down, but it is instead being designed from the ground up, enabled by hardware advances, and existing software. This is why I predict that it will be a success, assuming a designer does not layer something designed in a vacuum in to the product which could very well kill it, like some fancy payment system, or a super cloud.</p>
<p>Well I hope this has been enough to convince you that designing from top down is at least not as useful as it would be from the ground up, I often see the former being enacted, and inevitably failing, and the blame being cast on to non-belivers, poor marketing, or claiming that the true vision was never actually tried, when the true source of the fault is very clearly the source of the design itself, a vacuum.</p>
<p>Good design is not constructed in a vacuum, it is enabled, choose your methods wisely young designers.</p>" nil nil "4ba4e89d8eeceb12ac3244a8c0b010ab") (424 (20984 50462 20170) "http://oduinn.com/blog/2013/07/25/infrastructure-load-for-june-2013/" "John O'Duinn: Infrastructure load for June 2013" "John" "Thu, 25 Jul 2013 22:24:11 +0000" "<ul>
