<p>You can sign up for the event at the link above.* Note that spaces are limited and children need to be accompanied.</p>
<p><strong>Come and make something awesome with the Web!</strong></p>
<p><em>* It would be amazing if you feel you’ve got the skills to come and help out with being a mentor.</em></p>" nil nil "abd9202991370f31b412d5ffe44ba07a") (289 (20954 29014 924749) "http://work.erikvold.com/addons/2013/07/07/no-twitter.html" "Erik Vold: No Twitter" "Erik Vold" "Sun, 07 Jul 2013 07:00:00 +0000" "<p>In honour of <a href=\"https://blog.twitter.com/2013/experimenting-with-new-ways-to-tailor-ads\">Twitter’s decision to start tracking how you browse the web</a> (<a href=\"http://lifehacker.com/twitter-wants-to-start-tracking-you-on-the-web-heres-661569459\">read about it on Lifehacker here</a>) I have made <a href=\"https://addons.mozilla.org/firefox/addon/no-twitter/\">an add-on</a> to help us block Twitter from doing so.</p>
<h3>No Twitter</h3>
<p>The <a href=\"https://addons.mozilla.org/firefox/addon/no-twitter/\">No Twitter add-on for Firefox</a> was designed to block all images, css, javascript, everything from twitter’s domains from entering any other domain that you visit across the web.</p>
<p>However, I have allowed twitter to load assets on it’s own domains still so that you can still use the site to read/write tweets if you’d like to.</p>
<p>I’m sure that twitter will be tracking the links you click while you are visiting their site though, so far I have not added protection against that, but I plan to!</p>" nil nil "ebe387e3929d115447edc5bb43cab4df") (288 (20954 29014 924376) "http://work.erikvold.com/2013/07/07/why-voldzilla.html" "Erik Vold: Why Voldzilla?" "Erik Vold" "Sun, 07 Jul 2013 07:00:00 +0000" "<p>I’m nearly 30 now, so it has taken me a long time to figure out out why it is I keep getting up every day, I am sad to say, but then again how many people can articulate why it is they exist, and identify what motivates them? I suspect that those figures would be depressing..</p>
<p><a href=\"https://twitter.com/deezthugs\">David Dahl</a> asked me a good question at the last Mozilla Summit in 2010, well before I really started contributing to Mozilla. He asked, “What is it you want to do Erik?”, and I had no real answer, which depressed the hell out of me. At the time I had been writing quite a few UserScripts, Ubiquity commands, Jetpacks, and I loved Firefox which enabled all of this. I had also just started spending the time to figure out how Firefox extensions worked, and started contributing to my long time friend Greasemonkey which gave me great pleasure. I was out of work at the time, doing odd jobs here at there, surviving on the bare essentials, and spending all of my time in a dark room, coding my ass off.</p>
<p>It’s fair to say that I was not optimistic about the future. I could feel an undefinable drive to keep working, but I had no understanding why, nor belief that any of my efforts were worth while. My old friends from high-school were getting jobs at the post office and auto-repair shops, selling drugs or collecting unemployment checks, drinking away their nights, pissing away their days, and loving it as far as I could tell. While my old friends from UBC weren’t doing much better, and I had absolutely no interest in sharing their fates. So I avoided these people, they were and are nice people, and spending time with them in the past was an educating and empowering experience that I no longer had any use for. I felt quite alone, a feeling that has stayed with me since and had been hard to shake, until I visited Mozilla HQ.</p>
<p><a href=\"http://www.azarask.in/\">Aza Raskin</a> had saved me with a single email, asking me if I would be a Jetpack Ambassador, and unknowingly I started a meditation on what it meant (for me) to be a Mozillian, because I knew I would like to become one, or die trying.</p>
<p>Again, my drive was undefinable to me at the time, I could not really answer well enough (to satisfy myself) why it was I wanted to be a Mozillian. I had read <a href=\"https://www.mozilla.org/about/manifesto/\">Mozilla’s manifesto</a> and I liked it, but I could not say that it moviated me, I take too much pride in being a nonconformist to subscribe to a manifesto, and frankly I thought it was too internet specific, saying things like ‘the internet should be this’ and ‘the internet should not be that’ which is all well and good, but this was not going to be a document that got me out of bed every day. It is closer than anything I had ever read to this very day though.</p>
<p>It’s funny how a revelation can at once seem so awesome and so obvious at the same time. I’ve always known why I drag myself out of bed each morning, I just couldn’t say it. I want to empower others, through thought and deeds, I want to make life more secure and productive, for myself and others. I am by no means be the best or most capable at achieving this, and I’m certainly under no such illusion, but that is what motivates me and that is why Voldzilla exists.</p>" nil nil "c3b9c8751536084c4b850579ff21a4f2") (287 (20954 29014 923758) "http://feedproxy.google.com/~r/BenjaminKerensaDotComMozilla/~3/9q7RaF3E6zk/mozilla-at-oscon" "Benjamin Kerensa: Mozilla at OSCON" "Benjamin Kerensa" "Sat, 06 Jul 2013 23:45:15 +0000" "<p style=\"text-align: left;\"><a class=\"thickbox no_icon\" href=\"http://cdn.benjaminkerensa.com/wp-content/uploads/2013/07/mozilla_wordmark.png\" title=\"mozilla wordmark 300x121 Mozilla at OSCON\"><img alt=\"mozilla wordmark 300x121 Mozilla at OSCON\" class=\"size-medium wp-image-1973 aligncenter\" height=\"121\" src=\"http://cdn.benjaminkerensa.com/wp-content/uploads/2013/07/mozilla_wordmark-300x121.png\" title=\"Mozilla at OSCON\" width=\"300\" /></a>If you are attending O’Reilly Open Source Convention this year then be sure to attend one of the great talks being given by Mozillians this year:</p>
